PART 1: MATERIAL OVERVIEW
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

DESCRIPTION:
A matching game consisting of 20 wooden tiles (10 pairs) arranged on a wooden tray. Each pair consists of:
- One tile showing quantity (dots/objects)
- One tile showing the corresponding numeral (0-9)

The child matches quantities to numerals, reinforcing number recognition and one-to-one correspondence while developing visual memory and concentration.

MATERIALS NEEDED FOR CONSTRUCTION:

Physical Components:
□ 20 wooden tiles (5cm x 5cm x 0.5cm each)
□ 1 wooden tray with compartments (30cm x 20cm x 3cm)
□ Red acrylic paint (for dots)
□ Black permanent marker (for numerals)
□ Clear wood sealant
□ Fine sandpaper (220 grit)
□ Small felt pads (for tile bottoms)

Tools Required:
□ Hand saw or table saw
□ Ruler and pencil
□ Paintbrushes (fine tip)
□ Sandpaper block

Estimated Construction Time: 4-6 hours
Estimated Cost: $25-35 USD

MONTESSORI PRINCIPLES EMBODIED:

✓ Isolation of Difficulty: Focuses solely on quantity-numeral association
✓ Control of Error: Self-correcting through visual matching
✓ Concrete to Abstract: Bridges concrete quantity and abstract symbol
✓ Auto-Education: Child can verify own work independently
✓ Prepared Environment: Organized, complete, beautiful material

