PRESENTATION STEPS (FIRST LESSON)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

PART A: INVITATION & PREPARATION

Step 1: Invite the Child
"Would you like to work with a new number game? This is the Number Memory Game."

Step 2: Bring Material to Work Area
• Child helps carry tray to prepared work mat
• Place tray at top center of mat
• Teacher sits to child's dominant hand side

PART B: INTRODUCTION TO MATERIAL

Step 3: Name the Material
"This is the Number Memory Matching Game. We're going to match numbers with their quantities."

Step 4: Remove Tiles from Tray
• Remove all numeral tiles, placing them in random order on left side of mat
• Remove all quantity tiles, placing them in random order on right side of mat
• Set empty tray aside

PART C: DEMONSTRATION (Three Period Lesson Format)

FIRST PERIOD: NAMING

Step 5: Introduce Small Set (Start with 0, 1, 2)
• Place numeral "0" in work area
• Point to it and say: "This is zero"
• Place quantity tile (blank) next to it
• Point to it and say: "This is zero - no dots, nothing"
• Slide them together to make a pair

Step 6: Continue with 1 and 2
• Repeat process with numeral "1" and quantity (one dot)
• Repeat process with numeral "2" and quantity (two dots)
• Now three pairs are visible

SECOND PERIOD: RECOGNITION

Step 7: Test Understanding
• Mix up the three quantity tiles
• "Can you find two?" (child points or selects)
• "Can you find zero?" (child responds)
• "Can you find one?" (child responds)
• Repeat several times with variations

THIRD PERIOD: RECALL

Step 8: Assess Recall
• Point to quantity tile with two dots: "How many is this?"
• Point to blank tile: "How many is this?"
• Point to tile with one dot: "How many is this?"

PART D: INDEPENDENT MATCHING PRACTICE

Step 9: Child's Turn (Limited Set)
• Separate the three pairs again
• "Now you match the numbers with their quantities"
• Child works to match all three pairs
• Observe without interrupting

Step 10: Verification
• Once child finishes: "Let's check your work together"
• Review each pair: "Two dots... and the number 2. That matches!"
• Celebrate accuracy; gently correct any errors by modeling

PART E: GRADUAL EXPANSION

Step 11: Add More Numbers (Over Multiple Lessons)
• Session 2: Add 3, 4, 5 (now working with 0-5)
• Session 3: Add 6, 7 (now working with 0-7)
• Session 4: Add 8, 9 (complete set 0-9)
• Only advance when child shows mastery of current set

PART F: CLOSING

Step 12: Return Material
• Child matches all pairs one final time
• Return tiles to tray in organized fashion
• Carry tray back to shelf together
• "You did beautiful work matching quantities and numbers!"

