PART 7: PARENT COMMUNICATION GUIDE
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

HOW TO EXPLAIN THIS WORK TO PARENTS:

"Your child is working with the Number Memory Matching Game. This material helps them connect the quantity they see (dots) with the symbol they read (numeral). It's like when we see three apples, we know that's the number '3' - this game practices that connection. Strong quantity-numeral association is essential for all future math learning, including addition, subtraction, and even multiplication."

WHAT PARENTS CAN DO AT HOME:

□ Play "I Spy" with numbers: "I spy a number 4 on the clock!"
□ Count real objects and write the numeral: "Five cookies... let's write a 5"
□ Use playing cards (Ace through 9) for matching quantities to numbers
□ Point out numbers in daily life (addresses, prices, page numbers)
□ Avoid flashcard drilling - keep it playful and contextual

RED FLAGS TO WATCH:

If child shows these signs, may need additional support:
• Consistent reversal of 6 and 9 after repeated practice
• Inability to count objects past 5 accurately
• No recognition of any numerals despite practice
• Extreme frustration or avoidance of number work
→ Consider vision screening, additional one-to-one practice, or consultation with early childhood specialist

