TEACHER REFLECTION NOTES
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Why I Created This Material:
I noticed several children in my class had mastered Number Rods and Sandpaper Numbers but still showed hesitation when connecting quantity to symbol in new contexts. They needed more practice in a game format that felt less formal than traditional math materials. This matching game provides that bridge - it's engaging, self-correcting, and can grow with the child through variations and extensions.

Challenges Encountered:
Initially, I didn't include zero in the set. After observing children's work, I realized the blank tile representing zero was crucial for complete understanding of the number system. The tray organization also required adjustment - separating quantities from numerals with a divider reduced confusion during cleanup.

Future Improvements:
I may create a second set with different quantity representations (tally marks, ten frames, or actual objects) to further develop flexible number sense. The current dot pattern is excellent but could be supplemented with additional visual formats.

